  "prompt": "Were humans ever subject to natural selection?",
  "response": "Yes, humans have been subject to natural selection, just like all other living organisms. Natural selection is the process by which certain traits become more or less common in a population due to the differential reproductive success of individuals with those traits. \n\nFor much of human evolutionary history, individuals with traits that enhanced survival and reproduction in their particular environment were more likely to pass those traits on to the next generation. Over time, this led to adaptations suited to various environments. For instance:\n\n- Physical adaptations such as skin color, which evolved as an adaptation to varying levels of UV radiation in different parts of the world.\n- Lactase persistence in populations that historically practiced dairy farming, allowing adults to digest lactose.\n- Resistance to certain diseases, such as malaria, through genetic mutations like the sickle cell trait in regions where malaria is endemic.\n\nThese examples demonstrate how natural selection has shaped human populations. While modern technology and medicine have altered some selective pressures, humans are still subject to evolutionary processes.",
